The paper deals with the complexity of strategies in concurrent stochastic games, which is a topic that falls under game theory (cs.GT). The use of stationary strategies and the consideration of reachability and safety objectives suggest a connection to artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The analysis of the complexity of strategies involves the use of probability distributions, which is a topic in data structures (cs.DS). The study of stationary epsilon-Nash equilibria and the consideration of multiple players suggest a connection to machine learning (cs.LG). Finally, the use of probability distributions and the analysis of strategies in a concurrent setting suggest a connection to control theory (cs.SY).
